metadata.name: Mandelroid #88
metadata.description:
The Mandelbrot set is a mathematical object that is generated by a simple formula, and it exhibits some interesting visual patterns that are reminiscent of those found in nature, such as the self-similarity of branching structures, the repetition of small-scale patterns on larger scales, and the presence of chaotic behavior.

The beauty of Polaroid film lies in its ability to capture and preserve a moment in space and time in a unique and tangible way.

This work combines two things that are incongruent with each other and brings them together to create a digital memory that serves as a reminder that complexity can be found even in the simplest things, that art is intrinsic to nature itself.

• press '1' to scale the photo to 1024x1024 pixels (the default output)
• press '2' to scale the photo to 2048x2048 pixels (Warning: can be slow!)
• press '3' to scale the photo to 4096x4096 pixels (Warning: can be very slow!)
• press 'd' to save the Mandelbrot Set
• press 's' to save the Polaroid film

Done with p5.js
Simone "OuterSilent" Ferrari | @outertales | December 2022

metadata.name: Woo[p]-2.0 #28
metadata.description:
Hi all! Exactly 1 year has passed since I found out about this amazing fx(hash) platform. I am truly glad that I started working here. During this time, I have released more than 160 separate collections. I am also extremely grateful to all collectors, authors, designers and artists whom I met during this time. You are wonderful people. Once again I want to express my gratitude to everyone who minted my work and help financially in such a difficult time. Each coin is very important and has played a critical role in my life.

This collection has a final cost of 0 XTZ. If suddenly you like the minted work and you want to express your gratitude, you can write to me on Twitter, retweet or mint any other work from my profile. Only at your request.

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Dapperu #143
metadata.description:
Go bold, Dapperu!

Dapperu is the first generative animated GIF avatar.

A single Dapperu has 13 traits that result in different colors, shapes and movements. Every Dapperu is unique and can be used as a GIF wherever you like.

You can right-click the image and save it as a GIF file.

You can also press [control / command + s] or [tap and hold outside the image] to save a ZIP file that contains the GIF and all individual frames as SVG images.

© 2022 Dapperu.

metadata.name: Tunnels #257
metadata.description:
"Tunnels" explores using generative backgrounds to lead a field of isometric shapes. How the foreground and background interact varies wildly from generation to generation. "Tunnels" can seem to have an exit and sometimes seem to lead into nowhere.

Royalties Splits:
50% Donation to minter

Features:
Four different sizes: 9x16, 11x14", 12x18", 12x12"
Portrait or landscape orientation
~500 color pallets, one black and white, one cyan, magenta, yellow and black, and the rest from Jam3/nice-color-palettes.

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
@liamegan1/fxhash-helpers
@altesc/stdio

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: Future Echoes #110
metadata.description:
Future Echoes is a Generative Art experiment showing how a minute change in initial conditions can give rise to vastly different outcomes.

Created using pure JavaScript, without external libraries.

:: STYLES ::

- Pencil ----------- 68.5%
- Chalk ------------ 16%
- Biro ------------- 8%
- Error ------------ 4%
- Blueprints ------- 2%
- Final Warning ---- 1%
- Neon ------------- 0.5%


:: INSTRUCTIONS ::

- Add ?fullScreen=true to the url to render at full screen size
- To download the image in PNG format, press [s].

metadata.name: 1984 (TEZ) #19
metadata.description:
I was born in 1984.

Not all stripes were created equal. Stripes could represent barriers, restrictions, and the feeling of being controlled by societal norms. This darker side of the stripes reflects the anxieties and political climate of 1984. From playful pop culture to thought-provoking social commentary, these elements continue to inspire and challenge us. Stripes became a tool to explore the relationship between the artwork and the observer, questioning the very nature of what we see.

Made with p5js.
March 2024
Also available on Base ETH

Obsukiy is a french painter and digital artist based in Berlin.
https://twitter.com/ObsukiyArt
